### D. Salt Preparation (Insoluble by Precipitation)

**Cation Source Pool (soluble):** Pb(NO₃)₂, AgNO₃, BaCl₂, CuSO₄, CaCl₂, FeSO₄, FeCl₃ 
**Anion Source Pool (soluble):** KI, KBr, NaCl, NaBr, NaI, Na₂SO₄, dil. H₂SO₄, Na₂CO₃, K₂CO₃, NaOH, KOH 

**Feasibility Rules - INSOLUBLE PRODUCTS ONLY:**

| Product | Colour | Formation Rule |
|---------|--------|----------------|
| AgCl | White (turns purple in light) | Ag⁺ + Cl⁻ → AgCl(s) |
| AgBr | Pale yellow | Ag⁺ + Br⁻ → AgBr(s) |
| AgI | Yellow | Ag⁺ + I⁻ → AgI(s) |
| PbCl₂ | White | Pb²⁺ + 2Cl⁻ → PbCl₂(s) – soluble in hot water |
| **PbBr₂** | White | Pb²⁺ + 2Br⁻ → PbBr₂(s) |
| PbI₂ | Bright yellow | Pb²⁺ + 2I⁻ → PbI₂(s) |
| PbSO₄ | White | Pb²⁺ + SO₄²⁻ → PbSO₄(s) |
| BaSO₄ | White | Ba²⁺ + SO₄²⁻ → BaSO₄(s) |
| CaCO₃ | White | Ca²⁺ + CO₃²⁻ → CaCO₃(s) |
| BaCO₃ | White | Ba²⁺ + CO₃²⁻ → BaCO₃(s) |
| CuCO₃ | Green | Cu²⁺ + CO₃²⁻ → CuCO₃(s) |
| Cu(OH)₂ | Blue | Cu²⁺ + 2OH⁻ → Cu(OH)₂(s) |
| Fe(OH)₃ | Red-brown | Fe³⁺ + 3OH⁻ → Fe(OH)₃(s) |
| Fe(OH)₂ | Green (turns brown) | Fe²⁺ + 2OH⁻ → Fe(OH)₂(s) |
| Mg(OH)₂ | White | Mg²⁺ + 2OH⁻ → Mg(OH)₂(s) |

**DO NOT USE** combinations that produce soluble salts (e.g., NaCl + KNO₃ produces no precipitate)

**Structure D1 (Theoretical Yield of Precipitate - with Limiting Reagent):**
> "A student mixes **[VOLUME_1]** cm³ of **[CATION_SOURCE]** solution (concentration **[CONC_1]** mol/dm³) with **[VOLUME_2]** cm³ of **[ANION_SOURCE]** solution (concentration **[CONC_2]** mol/dm³). The precipitate **[INSOLUBLE_PRODUCT]** formed is filtered, washed, and dried."
> 
> **[RAM_INFO]**
> 
> *[Task: Determine the limiting reagent and calculate the theoretical yield of the precipitate in grams.]*

**Structure D2 (Purity of a Salt Sample):**
> "A **[MASS]** g sample of impure **[COMPOUND_CONTAINING_CATION]** is dissolved in water and made up to **[FLASK_VOL]** cm³. A **[ALIQUOT]** cm³ portion is treated with excess **[ANION_SOURCE]** solution. The precipitate of **[INSOLUBLE_PRODUCT]** formed has a mass of **[PRECIPITATE_MASS]** g after drying."
> 
> **[RAM_INFO]**
> 
> *[Task: Calculate the percentage by mass of **[CATION]** in the original sample.]*

**Structure D3 (Concentration from Precipitation):**
> "Excess **[ANION_SOURCE]** solution is added to **[VOLUME]** cm³ of a solution containing **[CATION]** ions. The precipitate of **[INSOLUBLE_PRODUCT]** is filtered, dried, and found to have a mass of **[MASS]** g."
> 
> **[RAM_INFO]**
> 
> *[Task: Calculate the original concentration of **[CATION]** ions in mol/dm³.]*

**Structure D4 (Mixed Halides - Sequential Precipitation):**
> "A solution contains both chloride and iodide ions. A **[VOLUME]** cm³ sample is treated with excess silver nitrate solution. The mixed precipitate of AgCl and AgI has a total mass of **[MASS_TOTAL]** g. The precipitate is then heated in a stream of chlorine gas, converting all AgI to AgCl. The final mass of pure AgCl is **[MASS_FINAL]** g."
> 
> **[RAM_INFO]**
> 
> *[Task: Calculate the original concentrations of Cl⁻ and I⁻ in the solution.]*

